more emotionally than it did logically but it's

20:22.500 --> 20:26.600
more or less a leper colony and again it's got this theme

20:26.600 --> 20:30.880
of an exiled group that's exiled because they have

20:30.880 --> 20:34.940
this disease and it's got some characters that are really hurting

20:34.940 --> 20:38.380
that sort of thing one of the questions I wanted to ask you about that was

20:38.880 --> 20:43.120
which I want to talk about some other things later is the Spanish influence

20:43.120 --> 20:47.320
did your experiences in Spain have anything to do

20:47.320 --> 20:49.420
with this story or did it come from something else

20:51.100 --> 20:55.740
there were several influences on that particular story and I would say that the Spanish influence

20:55.740 --> 20:59.320
the fact that I attended my last year of high school

20:59.320 --> 21:03.260
in Spain and an American dependent school outside of Seville

21:03.260 --> 21:06.100
did have an influence partly because

21:07.080 --> 21:11.260
the one foreign language that I have is Spanish that's the one foreign language

21:11.260 --> 21:14.940
that I can deal with with any degree of authority and also that helped

21:15.580 --> 21:18.760
the other two influences on that particular book however

21:18.760 --> 21:21.620
were a book

21:22.620 --> 21:27.120
I can't remember the author's name at this point but it was a study of the

21:27.120 --> 21:31.020
Aztec civilization and Aztec culture and at the same time

21:31.020 --> 21:35.160
another book about Father Damien who was

21:35.160 --> 21:38.600
the leper priest on Malachi

21:38.600 --> 21:40.960
an island in the Hawaiian group

21:42.380 --> 21:46.620
and so my disease muformacy as I call it in that particular

21:46.620 --> 21:50.480
novel stolen faces is a variety of leprosy I say as

21:50.480 --> 21:54.100
much in the course of the novel itself except that it can

21:56.740 --> 21:58.080
affect somebody

21:58.080 --> 22:02.500
even in a temperate climate or a cold climate as well as a tropical

22:02.500 --> 22:06.760
climate which is where Hanson's disease or leprosy usually strikes

22:06.760 --> 22:09.860
the whole point of the book really though was to

22:10.650 --> 22:14.580
examine the nature of prejudice and also what prejudice itself does

22:14.580 --> 22:18.140
to those who are discriminated against

22:19.680 --> 22:22.880
and really that's the point

22:22.880 --> 22:24.960
of inspiration for stolen faces

22:29.680 --> 22:30.380
Transfigurations

22:30.380 --> 22:34.260
was the next novel and it was a continuation of

22:34.260 --> 22:36.280
death and designation among the Asahdi

22:38.980 --> 22:42.160
I figured it was in the same universe as

22:42.160 --> 22:46.120
stolen faces and to me the Asahdi were

22:46.120 --> 22:50.320
really alien which again I think real aliens would be and this was

22:50.320 --> 22:53.880
an anthropology study and it was also as I said a continuation

22:53.880 --> 22:57.700
of the death and designation did you just

22:58.180 --> 23:02.100
that story you liked the background that's worth thinking

23:02.100 --> 23:05.560
did you always have the idea of completing it and making a novel out of it

23:07.720 --> 23:10.020
No, I never always had the

23:10.020 --> 23:13.800
idea I think when I wrote that story back in 72 or 73

23:13.800 --> 23:17.280
that I felt that I was pretty much finished with it that it was complete

23:19.320 --> 23:21.800
by the time I actually undertook

23:22.360 --> 23:25.480
to do transfigurations I had thought some more about

23:26.100 --> 23:29.400
the characters in that story both the humans and the aliens

23:29.400 --> 23:33.280
and I had also done a great deal of reading on human

23:33.280 --> 23:36.880
origins a lot of which

23:37.360 --> 23:41.260
I worked into the novel that followed that one No Enemy But Time but

23:41.260 --> 23:45.380
at the same time I guess I was

23:45.380 --> 23:49.160
really kind of laying the groundwork for No Enemy But Time with the research

23:49.160 --> 23:53.460
that I did that carried me through transfigurations the reason

23:53.460 --> 23:56.840
that I probably expanded transfigurations or

23:56.840 --> 24:00.940
death and designation among the Asadi into a full length novel that

24:00.940 --> 24:05.120
I called transfigurations is that by that time I was a full time writer

24:06.280 --> 24:09.160
I knew that this was one of my most popular stories

24:09.160 --> 24:11.960
that there had been questions about it some of the

24:12.620 --> 24:16.880
Luthians had not been tied up and I wanted to deal with

24:16.880 --> 24:20.340
the material again and I wanted to deal with it from

24:20.340 --> 24:24.460
from the perspective of my new knowledge about human origins

24:24.460 --> 24:27.860
and primate ethology that sort of thing

24:27.860 --> 24:31.140
so that was one of the reasons that I went ahead

24:31.920 --> 24:35.320
used the original novella as part of the text and created

24:35.320 --> 24:40.100
a good deal of more information about new characters

24:40.740 --> 24:44.480
and a sequel to the original novella in the course of the novel

24:47.020 --> 24:47.900
This is

24:48.320 --> 24:52.440
one of those real obvious questions but I have to ask it because I do want to know the answer too

24:52.440 --> 24:54.800
In transfigurations

24:54.800 --> 24:59.540
the aliens eyes are very important

24:59.540 --> 25:02.520
of course a funeral for the eyes of fire or eyes of fire

25:03.280 --> 25:08.060
just the title that goes without saying that they are and also the house of compassionate shares

25:08.060 --> 25:12.040
and pinion fall the eyes are really important

25:12.040 --> 25:16.240
so it seems to me that you have kind of not a fixation

25:16.240 --> 25:18.860
but they obviously symbolize something

25:18.860 --> 25:20.240
is that true?

25:21.900 --> 25:25.760
Well I would say that the eyes certainly do symbolize something

25:25.760 --> 25:29.980
I don't know whether I want to go a whole lot further than that

25:29.980 --> 25:33.840
I guess that it has always seemed to me that the eyes

25:35.600 --> 25:39.040
are what's the old cliche the windows of the soul

25:40.060 --> 25:42.720
and for an alien species I think they would be

25:43.640 --> 25:46.520
similarly a means of looking into

25:47.340 --> 25:50.320
the heart of the creature who has those eyes

25:52.140 --> 25:54.460
I think too I was looking early on

25:54.460 --> 25:58.340
when I wrote the early story pinion fall which was my first story I was looking for

25:58.340 --> 26:02.460
a way of making my aliens seem alien and one of the ways

26:02.460 --> 26:06.000
was to describe them physically and one of the most outstanding characteristics

26:06.520 --> 26:10.740
of any creature I think are the eyes

26:10.740 --> 26:13.980
and how they differ from one species to another so

26:13.980 --> 26:17.420
the aliens in pinion fall had eyes like insects

26:19.040 --> 26:22.000
in a funeral for the eyes of fire

26:22.000 --> 26:25.780
I guess I was again looking for a means, an exotic means

26:25.780 --> 26:30.120
of establishing the fact that my aliens were

26:30.120 --> 26:33.700
truly alien and by giving them different

26:33.700 --> 26:37.220
eyes, eyes like gems that was one way of doing that

26:37.860 --> 26:40.880
there may have been some subliminal influence too from

26:40.880 --> 26:43.780
one of the novels of Ursula Le Guin

26:44.800 --> 26:47.440
I'm trying to think now which was a city of illusions

26:47.440 --> 26:52.740
I think one of her characters has very very strange eyes but Ursula Le Guin has been an influence

26:52.740 --> 26:57.260
on me from way back and maybe that came into it to some extent too

26:58.600 --> 27:00.940
as far as the eyes of the Asadi go

27:00.940 --> 27:04.900
and the fact that they are a means of communication as well as

27:04.900 --> 27:08.820
a means of seeing and also a means of feeding when you discover that

27:08.820 --> 27:12.800
they enabled these creatures to photosynthesize part of their food

27:14.000 --> 27:16.960
I think there I was looking at the eyes in a functional

27:16.960 --> 27:20.960
sense as well as in a symbolic sense as if they really

27:20.960 --> 27:24.480
were a physical component of their

27:24.480 --> 27:26.640
make up that could help them survive

27:29.820 --> 27:32.920
Knowing them in but time is also

27:32.920 --> 27:34.520
an anthropology book as you said

27:36.260 --> 27:38.820
you probably on this one had to do a lot of

27:38.820 --> 27:41.200
homework I would think for the prehumans

27:43.940 --> 27:46.580
Yes I've told people that I probably did

27:46.580 --> 27:50.780
three and a half to four years of research for that book and I believe that that's true

27:50.780 --> 27:54.560
and by that I don't mean that I was continuously researching and doing nothing

27:54.560 --> 27:57.200
else not writing anything else but only researching

27:58.340 --> 28:01.880
but I nevertheless did spend a great great deal of time

28:01.880 --> 28:05.600
reading material to make

28:05.600 --> 28:08.700
my proto humans my hominids in that book

28:08.700 --> 28:13.560
as near to the real thing as I could imagine

28:14.480 --> 28:18.220
so I read people like Lewis B Leakey

28:18.220 --> 28:22.000
and Mary Leakey and Richard Leakey the entire Leakey clan, Donald Johansson

28:23.100 --> 28:25.160
everything I could get my hands on

28:25.160 --> 28:29.720
and scientific journals and news magazines that related to

28:29.720 --> 28:33.280
new discoveries in East Africa, Tanzania, Kenya

28:33.280 --> 28:37.080
wherever they happened to be Ethiopia when Donald Johansson came along

28:37.570 --> 28:40.400
so yes I spent an awful lot of time researching

28:41.470 --> 28:44.660
the physical nature, the stature

28:44.660 --> 28:49.400
the possible lifestyles of these hominids but also the flora

28:49.400 --> 28:53.940
and fauna at the same period so that I could make a credible stab

28:53.940 --> 28:57.120
at what kinds of

28:57.120 --> 28:59.380
other animals they would encounter

29:00.080 --> 29:04.980
what kind of vegetation they would be living among, how they would have to go about their

29:04.980 --> 29:09.160
survival strategies in other words so yes that took me

29:09.160 --> 29:13.100
a lot of time. I found it very very enjoyable while I was

29:13.100 --> 29:17.260
doing and I really kind of put it out of my mind since then

29:17.260 --> 29:21.400
I imagine that I may come back to it later on but I have kind of

29:21.400 --> 29:22.780
set it aside since then.

29:23.960 --> 29:26.280
That book I personally viewed

29:26.280 --> 29:28.620
is kind of a two-ponged

29:31.820 --> 29:32.420
oh

29:33.940 --> 29:38.260
it had two facets okay that engage me. One was the anthropology

29:38.260 --> 29:42.540
the lore and that sort of thing, that was fascinating but I also really liked the

29:42.540 --> 29:46.100
protagonist. He was really engaging, likeable

29:46.600 --> 29:50.360
and in science fiction you, especially modern science

29:50.360 --> 29:53.060
fiction, you don't often find that but I really like the guy.

29:54.080 --> 29:55.500
So I would assume that

29:57.300 --> 30:01.520
he just popped in your mind or does the character just form

30:02.400 --> 30:05.260
gradually and that's just how he turned out eventually.

30:06.320 --> 30:09.760
I will have to say that really he formed gradually over the

30:09.760 --> 30:13.200
composition of the book. There were a number of things that

30:15.040 --> 30:18.120
my plot dictated. I had to have a

30:18.120 --> 30:21.440
character who was somehow attuned to the distant past

30:22.120 --> 30:26.260
and particularly the distant past of Pleistocene East Africa and as a

30:26.260 --> 30:30.100
consequence I came up with a character who had vivid dreams even

30:30.100 --> 30:33.900
from his infancy on about this particular period

30:33.900 --> 30:38.420
so that his attunement to the Pleistocene in East Africa would make it possible

30:38.420 --> 30:40.820
later on for an Air Force

30:41.840 --> 30:45.840
time program to actually send him back bodily to that period

30:46.580 --> 30:50.000
or a simulacrum of that period as I explained it in the book

30:50.000 --> 30:53.660
so that much I knew I was going to have to give him.

30:54.140 --> 30:57.960
After that however I was really kind of on my own to come up

30:57.960 --> 31:01.780
with the sort of person that he happened to be and that unfolded

31:01.780 --> 31:06.140
for me gradually in the composition of the book and I was kind of surprised to discover

31:06.140 --> 31:09.820
who Joshua Campa really was or the kind of character

31:09.820 --> 31:13.920
that he really was and that was one of the nice things about writing the book too.

31:15.320 --> 31:17.760
Did you write the book in the order that

31:17.760 --> 31:21.720
we read it? In other words there are some alternating

31:21.720 --> 31:25.980
chapters past to present to past to present. Did you write it that way or did you

31:25.980 --> 31:28.360
write all the past and all the present and then cut them up?

31:30.640 --> 31:33.340
To tell you the truth I think I wrote

31:34.620 --> 31:37.820
alternating chapters. There were

31:37.820 --> 31:40.640
a couple of occasions when perhaps

31:41.660 --> 31:43.360
the episodes in the past

31:44.640 --> 31:48.560
I may have split them up and inserted a chapter from the present or from

31:48.560 --> 31:51.520
the near future but for the most part I actually did

31:52.320 --> 31:56.640
go back and forth. I did not write them in the order that they actually occur in the

31:56.640 --> 32:00.540
book however as a matter of fact the first thing in the book, the prologue, I wrote

32:00.540 --> 32:04.320
at the very end after I had completed the composition of the entire novel.

32:05.060 --> 32:08.660
I might also add here that David Hartwell, my editor

32:08.660 --> 32:12.380
at Timescape, was instrumental in helping me

32:12.380 --> 32:16.680
to cut down the book. It was considerably longer than it is

32:16.680 --> 32:18.560
now and it's quite a long novel anyway.

32:21.700 --> 32:24.820
He suggested the elimination of some chapters

32:24.820 --> 32:28.540
that were really kind of peripheral to the development of Joshua Kampa

32:28.540 --> 32:32.260
and also peripheral to the story of

32:33.160 --> 32:36.380
his return to and his life among

32:36.380 --> 32:40.700
the early hominids. So it would be

32:40.700 --> 32:44.460
difficult for me right now to reconstruct the exact order in which

32:44.460 --> 32:47.580
I wrote the individual chapters of that book but I did

32:48.620 --> 32:52.360
write some segments in the past, come and write some in the present

32:52.360 --> 32:54.980
and then eventually go back and

32:56.000 --> 33:00.020
kind of shuffle them together as if I were shuffling a deck of cards

33:00.020 --> 33:03.040
but perhaps and at least I hope so with a degree more

33:03.780 --> 33:06.260
not the same degree of randomness.

33:10.420 --> 33:11.000
I

33:11.000 --> 33:15.360
read, unfortunately I wasn't there but I read that in your nebula

33:15.360 --> 33:18.820
acceptance speech that you mentioned David Hartwell

33:18.820 --> 33:23.020
a couple of times and mentioned that he had been helpful so I take it that

33:23.020 --> 33:26.660
writers do appreciate it when good editors can come along

33:26.660 --> 33:31.040
and help them see the forest

33:31.040 --> 33:34.740
instead of the trees or the trees instead of the forest

33:34.740 --> 33:38.840
whatever you're supposed to say. Well I owe a special debt of gratitude

33:38.840 --> 33:42.760
to Hartwell. I would have to go back as far as a little

33:42.760 --> 33:47.040
knowledge for instance because he helped me with that book, he helped me with catacomb years

33:47.040 --> 33:50.580
and although he had moved over to Timescape

33:50.580 --> 33:54.540
which then was simply a pocketbook Simon and Schuster

33:54.540 --> 33:57.040
before he came up with the Timescape logo there

33:58.860 --> 34:01.400
but he helped me also with transfigurations

34:01.400 --> 34:04.840
in other words he was at Berkeley Putnam when that book was

34:04.840 --> 34:10.740
contracted for but he moved to pocketbooks before he had a chance to work on it.

34:11.120 --> 34:13.780
Nevertheless he did give me some help on it

34:13.780 --> 34:17.620
and he gave me a lot of help as I've indicated

34:17.620 --> 34:20.900
on no enemy but time. I don't know whether all writers

34:20.900 --> 34:24.120
appreciate that sort of editorial help and direction

34:24.120 --> 34:28.200
but I know that I can use it upon occasion and I think that

34:28.200 --> 34:31.340
Hartwell happens to be one of the people in the field who can give

34:33.500 --> 34:34.620
intelligent help.

34:37.300 --> 34:40.680
Under Heaven's Bridge was a collaboration with Ian Watson

34:40.680 --> 34:43.740
with whom you've collaborated on editing

34:43.740 --> 34:46.920
some short stories if I remember right since then.

34:47.520 --> 34:51.520
How did the mechanics of collaborating take place

34:51.520 --> 34:55.080
and I also wanted to venture a guess that the aliens were mostly you

34:55.080 --> 34:57.640
mostly your aliens. I just wanted to throw that in.

34:59.280 --> 35:01.840
Yeah the aliens really are my aliens because

35:03.220 --> 35:07.340
what he even wanted to do in fact what he suggested is that I write

35:07.340 --> 35:10.740
a story about the aliens the signosticoid from

35:10.740 --> 35:15.100
a little knowledge and catacomb years but rather than showing them

35:15.100 --> 35:19.380
in a human environment the urban nuclei that I take them and show them

35:19.380 --> 35:22.320
against their background of their home planet.

35:24.620 --> 35:27.100
