35:27.100 --> 35:30.600
we've been corresponding since about 1976 I believe

35:30.600 --> 35:35.480
and I wrote him a letter and said I'm really tired of those aliens

35:35.480 --> 35:39.240
I don't think I want to do anything else with them at all. I'm finished

35:39.240 --> 35:43.240
with them and he wrote back at that juncture and gave me

35:43.240 --> 35:45.960
a number of interesting ideas about them and said

35:47.820 --> 35:50.040
it's really too bad because there are lots

35:50.040 --> 35:53.980
of good things that we could still do with them and at that

35:53.980 --> 35:57.520
point we decided that maybe we could go ahead and collaborate on it.

35:58.100 --> 36:02.060
So the aliens were mine and he even wanted to see

36:02.060 --> 36:05.580
what they would be like on their own home world

36:05.580 --> 36:08.920
so we sent an expedition

36:09.460 --> 36:13.760
an earth expedition to their home planet and had them encounter

36:13.760 --> 36:17.760
those aliens there. We gave them a different name because we discovered a number of

36:17.760 --> 36:18.420
things about

36:21.180 --> 36:25.680
the star system 61's sickness is not really the kind of

36:25.680 --> 36:29.200
double binary that would support the kind of life that I had

36:29.760 --> 36:33.940
come up with in a little knowledge and catacomb years

36:33.940 --> 36:37.600
so we had to change a few things and so I think we called them kybers

36:37.600 --> 36:42.260
in Under Heaven's

36:42.260 --> 36:45.300
bridge which indicates that they are a kind of

36:45.300 --> 36:50.180
cyborg organism but naturally so

36:50.180 --> 36:54.600
that they evolved in that fashion and as far as the

36:54.600 --> 36:59.040
mechanics of the collaboration, Ian sent me about 30 pages of material

36:59.040 --> 37:02.380
which included a beginning, a middle and an end and suggested

37:02.380 --> 37:06.560
that we work from that as kind of an outline. I took those 30 pages

37:06.560 --> 37:10.280
and expanded them to about 100 and then we simply worked on

37:11.800 --> 37:13.760
in perpillating new chapters

37:14.280 --> 37:18.020
in that material. I believe Ian wrote the prologue to the

37:18.020 --> 37:22.040
book as well and I had final control over

37:22.040 --> 37:26.080
the entire manuscript just to make sure that the style

37:26.080 --> 37:27.680
was fairly consistent throughout.

37:31.620 --> 37:33.120
Kay, I want to

37:33.120 --> 37:37.120
get off now and ask a couple of questions about

37:38.020 --> 37:40.180
poetry and how it relates to your work.

37:41.060 --> 37:44.860
White Otters of Childhood which I said a while ago was my favorite

37:44.860 --> 37:48.420
story. The hero was Mark Cryer-Raines and he's a poet

37:50.400 --> 37:53.040
and he talks a lot about

37:53.040 --> 37:56.180
poetry in the story and he quotes poetry and he said

37:56.780 --> 38:01.080
there's a quote I remember one time where he said, you can't write poetry when your spirit

38:01.080 --> 38:05.060
is submerged. So I wanted

38:05.060 --> 38:08.940
to kind of delve into that. Is that you talking? Because you do

38:08.940 --> 38:12.900
write poetry and there must be some of you and him and is that true? Is that the way

38:12.900 --> 38:16.760
a poet works? Oh, golly. I think

38:16.760 --> 38:19.180
I probably ought to acknowledge

38:20.660 --> 38:24.720
a debt here to Roger Zalazny in particular. I don't know whether you know

38:24.720 --> 38:28.800
you must know. His early story arose from Ecclesiastes which has

38:28.800 --> 38:32.860
as its protagonist a poet and that story

38:32.860 --> 38:36.440
of his I believe, well it is, it's my favorite story of his

38:37.420 --> 38:40.460
and I think I was probably working with that

38:40.460 --> 38:44.920
story in mind when I wrote The White Otters of Childhood.

38:45.280 --> 38:48.620
I'll also have to say that I had read

38:48.620 --> 38:52.820
recently, by that I mean before I began writing

38:52.820 --> 38:57.080
The White Otters, I had read the poetry

38:57.080 --> 39:00.860
of St. John Perce who was a French poet,

39:00.860 --> 39:04.900
was a diplomat who also wrote poetry and he has a

39:04.900 --> 39:08.720
long poem called C-Marks and

39:08.720 --> 39:12.960
some of the lines in that particular poem suggested the title

39:12.960 --> 39:16.960
of The White Otters of Childhood to me and also the nature of the

39:16.960 --> 39:20.880
protagonist, also the nature of the mood that

39:20.880 --> 39:24.860
I tried to evoke in the story. I don't think anybody has

39:24.860 --> 39:28.800
really paid much attention to that or even noticed it even though I think I quote

39:28.800 --> 39:32.460
from him at the head of one of the sections of the story

39:32.460 --> 39:35.360
I use an epigraph of his at the head of one of the sections.

39:36.980 --> 39:40.620
As far as it being impossible to write

39:41.360 --> 39:45.160
poetry when the spirit is submerged, is that what I said?

39:45.460 --> 39:48.840
That's what you said. Okay, I would say that that's

39:48.840 --> 39:53.220
probably true. That disturbs me a little bit

39:53.220 --> 39:56.680
because I find that lately I've written less and less poetry.

39:56.680 --> 40:00.800
I'm not sure that my spirit is submerged so much as I am

40:00.800 --> 40:04.920
that poetry does not

40:06.380 --> 40:08.400
put food on the table whereas

40:09.960 --> 40:12.760
prose can sometimes do that. So I have written

40:12.760 --> 40:16.960
a lot more prose lately than I have poetry although I still like poetry

40:16.960 --> 40:18.720
and would like to be able to write more.

